Journal = {PLANT SYSTEMATICS AND EVOLUTION},
Year = {2024},
Volume = {310},
Number = {6},
Month = {DEC},
Abstract = {This phenetic study of the highly uniform series Laurifoliae of subgenus
   Passiflora combines analyses of 124 morphological markers on 151 plants
   from 13 species and AFLP markers from 99 DNA samples from 15 species,
   out of its 20 species. Seven vegetative and 21 floral descriptors were
   retained, based on their predominantly interspecific variation and
   allometric relations. Principal component analyses synthesize
   quantitative variation by two vegetative and five floral factors, none
   of them discriminating clearly among species. However, threshold values
   separating particular species could be used to categorize original or
   synthetic variables, and pool them with purely qualitative descriptors,
   particularly floral traits. The neighbor-joining analysis shows that
   morphological differentiation among Laurifoliae species is linked to
   particular combinations of traits shared by several species and not to
   exclusive traits. One of these combinations (presence of an inner series
   of filaments and wide or narrow trochlea) suggests coevolution with
   particular pollinators. The tree is consistent with the series taxonomy,
   despite the relative exception of a complex of white-flowered species
   around P. riparia. Similarly, the genetic analysis detects both limited
   interspecific variations and the absence of exclusive AFLP markers for
   any species. However, the resulting dendrogram shows interspecific and
   geographical differentiation acting at comparable levels: while most
   species are supported by particular clusters, others are split into
   geographical clusters or subclusters, suggesting some admixture. Neither
   morphological nor AFLP markers support the recent splitting of P. nitida
   into three distinct species, so P. coloranigra and P. brauliensis are
   reintegrated as synonyms in this taxon.},
